PMID: 3613916 [Indexed for MEDLINE]


349. Risk Anal. 1987 Mar;7(1):91-6. doi: 10.1111/j.1539-6924.1987.tb00972.x.

A method for estimating lifetime cancer risks from limited epidemiologic data.

Enterline PE.

Partly because of the poor quality of exposure information on humans, most 
lifetime carcinogenic risk assessments have been based on animal data. There 
are, however, surrogate measures for exposure that have not been fully utilized. 
One of these is duration of exposure where data on mean exposure levels are 
available. A method is presented for the use of such data, and the method is 
illustrated by developing a risk assessment from the available epidemiologic 
literature on gasoline and kidney cancer. This risk assessment is fairly 
consistent across studies and close to a risk assessment based upon an 
experiment with rats. While there needs to be much improvement in the quality of 
environmental data available to epidemiologists, it is possible that a number of 
risk assessments can be made from existing epidemiologic data and efforts 
directed away from extrapolation from animal data.

DOI: 10.1111/j.1539-6924.1987.tb00972.x
PMID: 3615996 [Indexed for MEDLINE]


350. Soc Sci Med. 1987;24(10):851-62. doi: 10.1016/0277-9536(87)90186-9.

Aging and health care utilization: new evidence on old fallacies.

Barer ML, Evans RG, Hertzman C, Lomas J.

The proportion of the population in the older age groups will increase 
dramatically over the next four decades. Furthermore, current per capita rates 
of hospital and medical care utilization rise sharply with age beyond the age of 
about 55. However, demographic trends alone do not imply health care cost 
increases in excess of what is supportable by normal economic growth. A 'cost 
crisis' will only occur if per capita rates of utilization among the elderly 
increase faster than for the general population. In this paper we present some 
descriptive data from published sources suggesting that this has been the case 
over the recent past in one Canadian province. The implications for the policy 
debate over the effects of an aging population are discussed.

